hat a life. She had a life - I often think about her you know, you see, it's open fires, we had no - closed ranges and - everything had to be boiled or stewed or something on here you know. Of course there was an oven, but - of course you know you don't p
u
t your oven on very often because it was a coal oven you know and took a lot of coal and - all this you know so - and mind, she baked every bit of bread, she baked everything that we ate you know, I mean, in the way of flour - she baked bread and teacakes
.
 Not very - and sometimes a bit of ginger cake, not very - not very grand things you know but still - and plenty of pies like rhubarb, nearly - nearly all the year round. Of course I mean - it wasn't forced rhubarb or anything like that you know, but plen
t
y of rhubarb in the garden you know and - well we thought it was nearly all the year round. Rhubarb pies. Oh well there was nothing like it - nothing like it is there you know. And you have to have - just take what you have. Mother - mother many times sai
d, now take what you have you'll never want. Oh dear.
